Introduction

Binary Conversions

  • Bits have assigned meaning by themselves, we interpret bits using different conventions
  • The bits 100011 could be interpreted as:
    • Natural number 67
    • Character C
    • Signed Integer -3
    • Address -61
    • Audio/Video/Image/etc.

Encoding Integers

  • For an unsigned integer, there are integers in 32 bits
  • n bits -> combinations
  • Which integers should be included?
    • For unsigned integers, we include the integers from to
    • For signed integers, we include the integers from to using Two’s complement
    • Therefore, operations such as +, * and - are the same for integers
    • However, / and comparison need separate operations

// LEC03 Sep.13

MIPS

Definitions:
An opcode is a word that represents a machine language instruction
Assembly language is a language for writing machine language program using opcodes and labels
An Assembler is a program that translate assembly language to machine languages

Instructions

Example: finding absolute value of $1

using only instructions

1.SLT(2,1,0) //the value in register 0 is always 0

2.BEQ(2,0,1) //if $2 is 0, skip next line

3.SUB(1,0,1)

4.JR(31) //exit the program

we can accomplish the same thing using labels

1.SLT(2,1,0)

2.BEQ(2,0,label)

3.SUB(1,0,1)

4.Define(label) // this line does not turn into machine code

5.JR(31)

Labels

Definition:
A label is a abstraction of a memory address.
A symbol table is a map from names [Label] to their meanings [memory address]

Note that:

  • In assignment 1, programs are Seq[Word]
  • In assignment 2, programs are Seq[Code]

How to eliminate labels:

  • We need two passes
    1. Determine addresses of each label => building the symbol table
    2. Convert uses of each label to address or offsets => using the symbol table

Relocation and Linking

Definition
An Object file contains machine language with extra meta data that records where labels are defined (-> symbol table ) and used
Linking is a process of combining objects files into one program or library. It involves 1.relocation and 2.resolving (or connecting) labels from different files
Relocation is the process of adjusting addresses in machine languages. So it can be loaded in different addresses

Consider the two code fragments below, the upper one calls the lower one as a procedure:

  • Now, if the two code segments are merged together and assembled together, everything should work.
  • However, it’s probable that the two code segments are assembled separately (e.g. for efficiency), thus something may go wrong.
  • Specifically, the symbol table.
  • That’s why we keep use(p)@4 and use(e)@4 in the object file.

  • now the address of label p is 12 and e is 24 by checking the symbol table, and this is called relocation // HOW??

  • To link assembly language files, just concatenate them together

  • To link object files:
    • reverse-engineer the labels from the metadata
    • relocation, label resolution across different files
    • concatenate assembly language programs
    • reassemble them to machine language

Variables

Definition
a Variable is an abstraction of a storage location that can hold a value
the extent of a variable instance is the time interval in which the variable can be accessed.

Variable kind Extent Implementation
Global entire execution of the program fixed location in memory
Procedure-local one execution of the procedure Stack (LIFO)
Field of an object object creation –> last use Heap

Stack

  • Designate register to hold address of top of the stack Stack Pointer $30
  • Push: subtract stack pointer by 4
  • Pop: add stack pointer by 4

Example: read c from the stack

1.LW(Reg1, 8, Reg30)
  • However, the offset 8 could be problematic since if new data are pushed onto the stack or data are popped, the STACK pointer Reg(30) will point to a different location:
  • At compile time, the CPU needs to create a symbol table for the offsets of the stacks.
  • At runtime, c should always be at the fixed position. But this way if the stack pointer changes, all the offsets mess up

Definition: a frame pointer is a copy of the stack pointer made at the beginning of the procedure call that does not change during the call. This enables us to change and use the stack pointer. MIPS convention $29

  • LW(Reg(1),8,Reg(29))
  • The idea is that if the stack is changed (push or pop) during the runtime, we can access the variable from the fixed frame pointer instead of the stack pointer
  • The convention in MIPS is to use register 29
  • In assignments, all data in memory are organized in chunks

Definition: A chunk is a consecutive memory locations. Offsets indexed by variables

Expressions

e.g. a*b+c*d

Technique 1: stack

//           a   *  b

def evaluate(e1 op e2) 

// generate code that evaluate e1 op e2

// at put result in $3

= block (

    evaluate(e1)

    ...

    evaluate(e2)

    ...

)

if we do 

block(

    evaluate(e1)

    $4 = $3

    evaluate(e2)

    $3 = $3 * $4

)
  • The problem is that if we use the register 4 here, inside the recursive call of evaluate e2, it may also overwrite the vale in register 4
  • We need a unique memory location
  • Thus we can use a stack to accomplish this 
block(

    evaluate(e1)

    push $3

    evaluate(e2)

    pop $4

    $3 = $3 op $4

)

the complete code example

What is the bad things about this code?

  • The code that it generates i very inefficient.
  • And it is hard to optimize the code

Technique 2: Variables

t1 = a * b

t2 = c * d

t3 = t1 + t2
  • if we separate the operations into variables, generating codes for this becomes easy
def evaluate(e1 op e2): (Code, Variable) = {

// generate code

// and put the result in a variable

    (c1, v1) = evaluate(e1)

    (c2, v2) = evaluate(e2)

    v3 = new Variable("temp")   

    code = c1 ++ c2 :+ v3 = v1 op v2

    (code, v3)

}

What is the good things about this code?

  • This code is going to be “easy” to improve
  • Register allocation

What is the bad things about this code?

  • v1 op v2: in machine languages, we only have operations on registers
  • Machine languages don’t directly support variables,
  • There might be many variables
